76561198050256667,Recommended,279440,16474956,"Posted: 17 June, 2015",all,franecki,"I've been a fan of Joe Dever's Lone Wolf books since they came out 31 years ago, and this game is an awesome continuation of the character and the franchise. It is mostly a choose-your-own adventure, with many skirmishes / combats sprinkled throughout the story. The combat system is a cute variation on standard ARPG: after choosing your action, movements of the mouse determine success/failure (pay attention when monsters attack you for your chance to dodge / block!).If you know the character, this is a great new story with Lone Wolf. If you don't know the character, it's still a fun gamebook in computer form, with _many_ hours of play and branching paths to explore. Either way, it's a win-win!!"
,Not Recommended,279440,13341620,"Posted: 13 December, 2014",all,The Black Knight of 2fort,"This is a recommendation that borders right on the 50ish out of 100 score, making it a toss-up between 'buy this' or 'don't buy this'.  Keeping in mind that I have yet to pass five or so hours in game yet and this is based only on the first chapter, my biggest problem is this.There is so.  Much.  RNG.Restating, there is nothing wrong with Random Number Generator-based anything.  Every game relies on RNG.  Sometimes your attack goes through, sometimes it's blocked, sometimes it's parried, sometimes you get lucky, sometimes not.  The problem with Lone Wolf is how shatteringly screwed you can be by the RNG, and there is not a single thing you can do about it.The fighting consists of two phases for you; an attack phase and a rest phase.  During your attack phase, a timer ticks down how long you have to make your attacks, drink your potions, etc.  You can do multiple things per turn, until you eat up all your END (physical actions), MANA (magic actions) or run out of time.  Your END recovers very slowly during your attack phase and very quickly during your rest phase, with your MANA barely recovering at all until you kill an enemy.  However, while YOU cannot attack in your rest phase, enemies can attack ALL THE TIME, operating on their own (hidden) attack and rest phases.  You can and will be interupted while you go to select an attack by an enemy launching his attack first, preventing you from acting on a strategy or idea.RNG as I already stated is beyond intolerable at times.  The very first attack launched against you, you might dodge.  Or  it can stun you, you lose your turn, and are unable to act while enemies deal 1500 damage to you (very realistic damage, considering even within the first 3-4 battles they start throwing 3 enemies at a time at you).  Or you might dodge all these attacks and then launch your own POWERFUL attack on an enemy.  He might take the hit and lose 50% of his health, or he might counter it, take 10% damage, and you have just wasted 50% of your END, better luck next time.The point of this is that it boils down to the right set of circumstances happening to let you succeed.  Being stunned in turn 1 can sometimes be an instant game-over, as you lose your turn and are reduced to nearly no HP and struggling to recover.  5 minutes into the fight, you might be selecting your sword to kill an enemy when he swigs back a potion (Even basic enemies have potions, by the way, hope you don't mind your fodder healing themselves), and he now has more HP than you can dish out, preventing you from killing him, preventing you from replenishing your mana, preventing you from healing the next round, meaning you died.And this is all topped off with the fact that you can restart every battle from the beginning.  So what happens?You restart.  A lot.Not even from dying, either.  Enemy dealt a shattering crit on their first move?  Restart, this time you parry it.  Enemy stunned you at the wrong time?  Restart, hope that doesn't happen this time.  I have had cases where I have restarted certain fights upwards of 15-20 times until the RNG simply decided it was a good time to let me win, and the enemies didn't pull any shenanigans and my attacks went off without a hitch.Bottom line of all this: The game is pretty and sounds nice, fantastic.  But the gameplay itself suffers horrendously not because of actual mechanics, but because all the behind-the-scenes calculations rely entirely on a very erratic RNG system that can leave you decimating your enemies easily or getting royally screwed over on your very first turn.  If you buy this game, be prepared to accept that a great deal of your time will involve slamming that ESC key, restarting the battle, and just praying that RNGesus is kind to you this time."
