,Recommended,279440,13130891,"Posted: 28 November, 2014",all,Hidden Inside,"The game is average, but it has its own uniqueness. Its like an interactive book with multiple tools to get the job done with slight variation to how the game unfolds.The narative is stylish and done close to how the upcoming 'Hand of Fate' is done, but is somewhat different. Its fancy, rich in details and vivid, making it really easy to picture the events unfolding. Seriously its like an ok fantasy book.Now the problems with the game are shallow crafting and loot systems, repetitive combat, customisation and soundtrack.The combat is semi turn based and is somewhat confusing for the 1st 3-6 minutes, then after a few hours of slaying monsters it gets rather repetitve and boring also easy *if you have chosen the perks right* or are willing to use potions.Crafting system exists but other then the 'inventory increase' the changes the crafted gear brings are minimal. The 'various weapons' are not so various at all its the same 3 weapons with slightly different stats and sometimes a different model. Now the animations are done well *even the comical faces of enemies during the mana restoration finishers* and the gameplay is on the point fluid, but with little variation to it it eventually will get dull no matter what. Too many battles with too little variation.Soundtrack was distracting and filled with disturbing background noises of a muted phone under a pillow a few meters away.Overall its a solid game, definite few hours of fun, unless  you are impartial to the storytelling narrative, which this game does great.Overall easy 6-7/10. Worth a puchase when its on sale."
76561198079020363,Recommended,279440,15897689,"Posted: 19 May, 2015",all,crickit90,"I'd never heard of Lone Wolf 24 hours ago. I paid $7.49 for this game, and it was beyond worth it. I've played just under thirty minutes. This game feels great. You get to create a customized character in minutes, those choices immediately affect the story you are reading and the combat you will face. The story events are between old school text based adventures and quick time events. It blends your decisions with your actions beautifully. The turn based combat doesn't let you walk away. You have limited time and resources to take actions, so you need to make snap decisions. To be effective you need to stay calm and focused. This makes the combat thrilling, and did I mention this game looks pretty too. The way they blend art from the book into the combat sequences is stunning. The graphics aren't what you would see on a next gen console, but they look good. As far as animation is concerned, I have to say they nailed it. From throwing knives to having your chest slashed open, the models move fluidly. I definitely recommend picking Lone Wolf up if you have $10 to spare.Edit: Now that I have almost ten hours under my belt, I would like to expand this review a little bit. I started another character because I didn't see how it was possible to survive without certain skills. Turns out I was wrong. You can definitely take whatever starting skills you are interested in trying. Sometimes enemies will wreck your day. When it happens, you may not even get to defend yourself because it is absolutely possible to become stun locked. It isn't likely, and because the game uses a random element, it is also completely possible for you to dodge every attack in a fight. You will probably die a couple of times during a fight that you are prepared for due to bad luck. It makes it far more rewarding when you try again and slaughter your enemies. If you really get stuck, the game even has the option to drop the difficulty a step when you retry. I should also talk about replay value after making a second character. It's okay. If you choose different skills at the beginning of the game, and you try taking another path through each of the obstacles in the game, then it isn't too repetitive. Many of the fights will be the same or nearly the same unless you had the option to avoid one completely. When you know what you are doing, you can definitely work through the fights faster, and it feels like you are accomplishing something rather than grinding because the story actually moves as you cut down your enemies. I can't say how long a run through this campaign should take. I just set the game on hard, turned off hints, and charged into the fray."
76561197993528201,Recommended,279440,13128795,"Posted: 28 November, 2014",all,Docco,"If you liked the Lone Wolf series back in the 80's, this is probably a childhood fantasy come to life.Be aware, this is an interactive book with more reading than anything else, but it is as well written as ever when it comes to Joe Dever's style.  Reading is separated by quick-time events - whether it's the combat system itself (there is a slight bit more to it than quick-time like picking what type of attack etc.) or an action event where you have to quickly react after you've made a questionable decision.As for everything else, you start off by choosing your gimmicks (animal kinship, camoflouge, mindblast, etc.) just like the good ole' days and it takes off from there.  The page artwork is fantastic (black & white pencil sketches like the books, but brought to life), and the combat uses 3D with pretty good quality models and environments.  Music is dynamic and quite well done (title screen reminded me of Loreena McKennitt).All in all, I give it two thumbs up (graciously donated by the the Giak I just killed)."
