76561197962557676,Recommended,279440,13122316,"Posted: 28 November, 2014",all,tbd_phant0m,Being a fan of the Lone Wolf books since the 80's so I may be biased with my quick review.For me it reads like a great Joe Dever RPG that he is so well known for. The fighting aspects of the game are very well done and involving. The quests within the story are very well put together.Being Lone Wolf in the world of Magnamund is a must for any fan of his work and the studio that have worked so hard to get it right have done a terrific job. Well done to all involved.Even if you are not familiar with Lone Wolf and the world of Magnamund you will not be disappointed. Give it a try and be one with the Kai.
,Recommended,279440,29378202,Posted: 20 January,all,Apoc,"You might have heard about Lone Wolf a long time ago, back when books were only on paper. It was also part of the pretty interesting genre of Choose Your Own Adventure that made you play a game while reading, perfect to get kids interested. I was pretty surprised to see a Lone Wolf video game, almost 25 years after I enjoyed some of those books.The game itself is a mobile port but it's actually pretty solid, it would not look like a mobile game if you removed those touchscreen controls. Everything is using the mouse like if it was your finger but it's really responsive and forgiving. Not once did I felt like I was playing a mobile game.The game is pretty unique, at its core it is an rpg with stats, abilities and inventory but it comes in two parts. The book is like a Visual Novel, a lot of text, some choices and very rare quick time events with some of those choices. Then there is the battle portion of the game where you use motions and clicks to battles some enemies. There are also two quick minigames, lockpicking and a puzzle cube. The book visuals are pretty sharp and stylished then the battle graphics are colorful and pretty detailed for a 15$ mobile port.The book portion is pretty linear, sometimes you have two or three paths but in the end they will all lead to the same end. There are multiple choices that affect the text but often also the battles, you might be able to skip a battle, start one with enemies on fire or with less enemies for example. Some of those choices are also limited by the abilities you picked at the character creation so it add a good amount of replayability while the story will still mostly be the same but with some different events.The battles are hit or miss. Depending on your character build you can have pretty close fights or you can have very unfair fight where you die in 5 seconds without having time to do any action or where you annihilate the enemies before they can act. It is very random but, to be fair, the books where also pretty random with battles using a random number table. I won't go into too much detail about the battle mechanic since the game gives tutorial prompts but it's pretty much all quick time event except some abilities without any prompt. You have a decent amount of time to do those prompt so it does not require lightning fast reflexes but messing up one prompt can mean losing a battle. There are no penalties to losing battles except the time lost because you can simply replay the battle as many time as you want, and you might need to do for some bosses or if you play on Hard.As for the story itself, it is separated in 4 acts, all with pretty different areas and at least one new enemy type each. Lone Wolf was inspired by Dungeon and Dragon so it will feel familiar if you are used to this type of fantasy. Most of the story is about getting from point A to point B evading or killing monsters, looting stuff and with two or three npc to interact with per act. It is a dark story, you can't save everyone and some of those choices can be pretty mean. Lone Wolf is an already developped character so you can't be evil and act any way you want but, while he is a hero, he is not totally good and actually pretty grey. I guess you could compare it to the Paragon and Renegade system in Mass Effect.Overall, if you can get past the pretty random filled battle system, it is a great game that is a very well though interpretation of the gamebooks genre. Sadly, Joe Dever passed away recently so it might be the last for Lone Wolf but they could use this system for other stories."
76561198040367630,Recommended,279440,13221639,"Posted: 3 December, 2014",all,Wolfman,"Have you ever heard of the books that this game is based on?  If not I highly recommend you engage in one of the best Choose your Own Adventure series of all time.  This game is based on one of my favorite fantasy worlds of all time.  And I say that without attempting to establish a bias.  Without lying, I am a total fan of the books and have wanted the IOS copy of this game for some time.  I just never had a phone that could run it.  That being said, I jumped on this as soon as it was available.  So was it worth it?Thus far, the issues that people may have with this game, is the fact that you are essentially, reading a modernized version of one of the choose your own adventure books.  There is no real vocal nararation outside of the introduction to each chapter.  Beyond that, you the player will be reading the book, and interacting with all the choices and game mechanics in a sort of quick time event laden skill test.  Now let me start by saying I hate quick time events.  I hate them.  But in this case, given the IOS port nature of the game, they are a tolerable evil, that still works with the game.I have not played the game to date on any difficulty below the hardest... and in doing so, I have found that I literally have to budget a strategy in fights down the the precise second of battle where I need to drink a potion.  Unfortunately, I have had a couple of moments where the games RNG has decided that I would not even get to take a turn as soon as battle starts before the enemy slaughters me with no quarter.  There is a heavy element of RNG, so I am not entirely keen on the idea of that being the only real difficulty.There is a lack of music variety, but what you get is good quality stuff.  The sound effects are also not ear sores.  The game also seems to come into a length of around two and a half to three hours per Act, with four Acts to complete the whole game.  That is a base estimate, it can easily be done faster, and again, I am on the hardest difficulty, so I am certain the game can be cleared much faster on the easier stuff.All and all this is a completely solid IOS port, fully playable with virtually no gameplay related issues, except for how the touch spots work.  The example is during combat, you can turn the combat, and the ""touch spots"" where you have to clic k to bring up your menus move with the joints they are attached too.  So lone wolf's sword has a touch spot half way on the blade.  As the sword moves, so does the touch spot, and if you rotate the camera to certain angles, the touch spot can end up overlapping other touch spots.  Not the best system, but it is at least functional, and tolerable without any really devistating moments where it screwed me out of a victory.I like this game, I find it worth the price of admission considering as a choose your own adventure, there are multiple possible routes through the game that can give alternating storylines.  Its interesting, but admitantly, might not be for everyone since you are literally reading a choose your own adventure novel.  Check it out, and if you are curious about where it comes from, check this link out:http://www.projectaon.org/en/Main/BooksThis is the site where you can play the entire book series leading up to the events of the game.Sub note, you don't need to have read the books to enjoy the game.  It just helps :D"
