,Not Recommended,279440,14197523,"Posted: 27 January, 2015",all,Nox,"Do you like QTEs designed for a different platform, no instructions, indescipherable lockpicking minigames and repetitive combat? Yes? Then you'll love this game. If not, I can't recommend it to you. As a long time Lone Wolf fan, I was eager to see what was on offer. Here's the good, bad and really bad.1) The Good: The artwork. It's a really lovely looking game ... and that's it. There's not really much of a story so far. The experience is much like reading a graphic novel in an uncomfortable chair that has a bit of wire sticking out and poking your back.2) The Bad: (i) Not really any instructions. Sometimes, the first time you do something, it will pop-up a tip advising you of a few details but I can't seem to find a way to get those tips back. And there's no instruction manual.  (ii) Not really a story so far (to be fair - the books didn't either, usually just along the lines of ""go to the capitol and warn the king"").  (iii) Every section is a fight, some sections more than one. You must take the Kai discipline of Healing. Every single action in the game is simple a progression to the next fight. It gets dull, fast.3) (a) It's all QTEs - and I have no idea what the contact point for half the QTEs are. Some of them seem really easy and almost impossible to fail, while there is another that I have never succeeded in hitting despite being absolutely certain that I did. (b) Sadly most people probably won't read this far but THE LOCKPICKING. It makes me weep. It's really that bad. There is no contact point to tell you when you have hit the sweet spot. The picks break instantly. When they break, your pick is set back to the original position, meaning you have to start from scratch. I had 12 lockpicks. I broke all 12 - on one lock! If you are presented with any other option than using a lockpick, please, for the sake of your sanity, take it!Thank you for reading."
