,Not Recommended,279440,17595037,"Posted: 18 August, 2015",all,XDVR,"The story is great - in the great tradition of classic game book romantic fantasy hokum, but you know what you're getting! The interface itself is beautiful, really nice and brilliant (although obviously a translation from a touch-screen/mobile device... don't be lazy, make it be PC specific!). The simple artwork animations do an amazing job of helping to invigorate the text and add to it. I cannot fault any of this - however amongst all this greatness there an utter and complete let down within the awful fighting mechanism.1) It feels like a JRPG - I know this is marmite, and I'm on the hate side of this. Does anyone actually like this rubbish mechanism? Anyone? You do? Why? Maybe you can expla... oh nostalgia... ok, so is there anything ACTUALLY good about it? No? Didn't think so... shall we all get over this nonsense and finally move on?2) They happen an awful lot and Lone Wolf seems completely ill-prepared and completely out-matched, it's a miracle he makes it through any battle. Also, so much randomness... again a fail-over over from JRPGs... at some point people will look back and go ""You know those Final Fantasy games came out at the same time as Planescape: Torment and Baldurs Gate and were immensely lame in comparison... why are we still copying them?"" Well... I don't know why anyone wanted to copy them instead of PT and BG in the first place, but who knows... maybe the dumbed down/random infuriating and thus dull reloading/restarting is for some people in the world that have nothing better to do. I however, want a game that has play-tested, balanced, and isn't JRPG. I'm sure even the patience of a Saint would be tried and have him throwing a controller around in frustration.3) All icons have cooldown on them... er... I have a cooldown on basic Attack/Defend? WHAT THE DICKINS?!?Who thought that was a good idea? Find them and give them a good slapping with a large wet fish.4) I have next 