,Recommended,279440,15941228,"Posted: 22 May, 2015",all,dpvhWYnpIwNT8BPQAOc9,"This game does the adventure book style of games very well, the writing is original and well done. I didn't think there would be a lot of content consideing the game is based on books, however it managed to entertain me with a 20 hour play through and a story that spans over many maps. As could be seen in the game's trailers, it mixes in turn based combat scenes and some event-driving mini games such as the lock picking  to enrich the experience beyond simply reading a book and making choices, which I think is a nice touch and makes the game more interesting and playable. The music is subtle, which doesn't seem like an important thing at first, but having played some other game-book inspired games with blaring music that just serves to distract me from my reading, it is important to have a good appropriate score to play to your game..It's an rpg which follows the typical strength-agility-intelligence attribute archetypes which each has a use in several aspects of the game, however it doesn't fix you to the predictable and boring stereotypes you often see associated to each.  (such as, intelligence typically being an attribute reserved for wizards who only do things such as cast spells and be wise, etc.) Rather, your chosen attribute gives you a headstart for making choices of that type easier to be successful, your choices increase your attribute scores when it comes to levelling up, giving the gamer much more freedom to play how they like in my opinion. The combat is ok, it is turn based and made interesting with qte-type events to determine some dodges and hits.I thotoughly enjoyed this game and would recommend it to anybody who is interested in a story and making choices with consequences."
76561198017241275,Recommended,279440,13729863,"Posted: 30 December, 2014",all,Lonewolf,"As someone who thoroughly enjoyed the book series I was excited to play this when I first heard of it. Having completed the playthough I found myself captured to the end and await a sequal.There is alot of parts to the game I found very enjoyable and not much I could point out for improvement, the game is a solid effort and well rounded. I really enjoyed both the combat and non-combat sections of the game and found it to be rather challenging, so felt rewarded when I had successes throughout the game.Story: The story of the game was done well much like the books were, I think it was a good implementation. Even where mistakes were made (I fell foul of a trap in the game after i thought i had overcome it...was cursing myself afterwards too haha), I was glad to see that it was indeed possible to make a story choice that would cost you your life in the game. Also reflecting on the game there were story choices that had both obvious outcomes and not so obvious outcomes which i thought was good, though personal preference would have me request more of the latter.Combat: As for combat... NAILED IT. I loved everything about the combat in the game. The combat mechanics were solid, i especially liked the fact you could overexert yourself at the expense of your own wellbeing.Some games allow you to adopt a fairly static playstyle, I usually find myself never really needing to use consumables... in this however they were very much a requirement, I actually found myself stocking up on poison arrows or throwing blades... I found myself throwing down stunpowder just to give myself some breathing room in some of the fights... I also found myself NOT doing area attacks in some situations because i didn't want to break the mindblast i did on an that Drakkarim... or chugging down a... stamina potion... just so I could disarm that vordak.I must say i never felt so relieved as when I took down 2 of those accursed things and a gourgaz that attacked me at once... that was a tough fight and I had to laugh when the giak came after the 3 of them fell and tried to be all tough.Actually if i had one criticism about the combat scenes... at the end of them there needs more variation in the post combat animations... usually he's just standing there with his 2 weapons (i ran with 2 axes or sword+axe) and kinda looked like a try hard.Bugs: - I didn't encounter a single bug... across the whole game...Audio: Sound track i found thematic and made good ambience, the sound effects from the fight scenes themselves were satisfying and not overdone or underdone, maybe some more variation in the enemy roars at the start of a fight scene would have topped it off. Instead of every enemy roaring, having curses, insults, shrieks, to mix it up a little would have staved off the little bit of repetiveness i noticed here. Same with grunts and shouts when executing attacks.Graphics: The graphics/Art tied in well to the feeling of the game i think that was trying to be achieved. The enemies all looked amazing, the last enemy of the game looked a bit cartoony i felt compared to the rest of the game(especially his death scene), but he was the pimped out big bad evil guy with ancient artifacts, so i get it.Overall if you ever read the books, you will probably enjoy this game as it's got the same feel (I found it slightly more casual than the books truth be told, but minor point).If you're new to the Lone wolf world then you will find this game refreshingly different to other RPG's, If you like challenges then i suspect you will like this game, as your choices do matter and affect your game experience with both positive and negative outcomes for the actions you take."
