76561198027221726,Recommended,279440,13487525,"Posted: 20 December, 2014",all,xaagon,"I recommend this, but I am biased as I've been a fan of the Lone Wolf gamebooks for the last 30 years.The game plays much like the game books.  Actually, you are basically reading the game.  It is presented as in a very old book, with pictures that move (similar to the pictures in the Harry Potter movies).  You will make decisions every few pages and it affects how your story is written.  At times, the game leaves the book and goes into more of a 3rd person view.  There is combat that is sort of turn based but not entirely - you have a limited amount of time and energy to do things on your ""turn"", but your opponents won't just be standing there the entire time.  When it's not your ""turn"" you are either defending or just standing there exhausted if you didn't save any energy after doing your attacks.  (Sorry if I've done a poor job explaining this - you may have to see it to understand.)  Outside of combat, there are other actions that require you to quickly follow arrows on the screen with your mouse to be successful.  You will improve your skills and acquire items that will help you in your mission.So for those of you familiar with the gamebooks, this is like one of those, with mini-games replacing the ""select a random number"" element.If you're looking for the next Skyrim, this may not be for you.  If you're a life-long Joe Dever fan then you should buy this immediately without any further thought whatsoever.  For all others I suggest watching a few minutes of game play on youtube to decide if this is something that you would like."
