,Recommended,279440,13398769,"Posted: 15 December, 2014",all,Snowz,"Best summarized as a choose your own adventure book, with quick time event combat.The game plays like reading a book, quite literally. You turn pages and read. Choices can be made, and those choices are determined by what skills you have. Picked agility? You can climb to the hole in the roof and peek inside. Got brute strength? Smash the door down and charge in. That kind of choice.The combat is kind of turn based, where you have a bar that expires slowly, and you can do more than one thing per turn at the cost of the bar going down. You select what enemy to attack, you select what weapon you will use, then select what attack to do with that weapon. After selecting what you want, you will perform that action, with mouse based quick-time-events, via dragging or clicking in time with the prompts.Thoughout the story, depending on choices made you have to solve puzzles or pick locks.Once you read a page, you can open your inventory, check stats, skills, map etc.I recommend this game, but with caution. Like, they advertise lock picking in the game description, as if it's some fancy feature, when it's basically just skyrims way of doing it. To me that was a warning sign, but don't let things like that deter you from buying the game.It's entertaining and i'm enjoying it, although i didn't expect it to be 90% reading when I bought the game.Also an annoying con, transitions take too much time. I click on something and gotta wait way to long for something to happen. I want to go to the inventory? Gotta wait for all that fading and animations to finish."
,Recommended,279440,21751701,"Posted: 10 March, 2016",all,Jala-chan,"A cross between a QTE-driven adventure game and a visual novel, this game has a fun story that holds true to the source material, a nice mix of narrative and action, and a great sense of empowerment as your character develops. The soundtrack is wonderful and the level of complexity is greater than your average visual novel or adventure game but not so detailed as to bog down play. It certainly has a high replay value in my mind given the branching paths and flexibility allowing you to solve problems by a variety of means depending on how you have built your character. A definite recommend for anyone who enjoys games such as Sorcery! or Telltale narrative-based titles."
